Consider the following code.

```java
int x = 5;
int y = 0;
if (y != 0 && x / y > 2) {
    System.out.println("yes");
} else {
    System.out.println("no");
}
```

What is printed when this code executes?

Consider the following code excerpt.

```java
String s1 = new String("hello");
String s2 = new String("hello");
System.out.println(s1 == s2);
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));
```

What output is produced?

Consider the following code.

```java
int n = 10;
boolean flag = (n > 5) || (n++ > 100);
System.out.println(n);
```

What value is printed?

Determine the value of `result` after the following code executes.

```java
int x = 8;
int y = 3;
boolean result = !(x > 5 && y > 5);
```

Consider the following code.

```java
boolean a = true;
boolean b = false;
boolean c = true;
if (!(a && b) || c) {
    System.out.println("X");
} else {
    System.out.println("Y");
}
```

What is printed?

Consider the following code.

```java
int a = 4;
int b = 7;
boolean result1 = !(a < 5 && b > 6);
boolean result2 = (a >= 5 || b <= 6);
System.out.println(result1 == result2);
```

What is printed?

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int x = 4;
int y = 10;
boolean flag = !(x > 5 || y < 8);
if (flag)
{
    System.out.print("pass");
}
else
{
    System.out.print("fail");
}
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int n = 0;
int k = 4;
if (n == 0 || k / n > 1)
{
    System.out.print("yes");
}
else
{
    System.out.print("no");
}
```

Determine the values of `x` and `y` after the following code runs:

```java
int a = 6;
int b = 9;
boolean x = !(a % 2 == 0 && b % 3 == 0);
boolean y = (a % 2 != 0 || b % 3 != 0);
```

What is printed as a result of the following code?

```java
int x = 0;
int y = 5;
if (x != 0 && y / x > 1) {
    System.out.println("big");
} else {
    System.out.println("small");
}
```

What is printed as a result of the following code?

```java
boolean a = true;
boolean b = false;
boolean c = !a || b;
boolean d = !(a && !b);
System.out.println(c + " " + d);
```

A programmer writes the following method intended to return `true` when `x` is **not** in the closed range `[low, high]`:

```java
public static boolean outOfRange(int x, int low, int high) {
    return !(x >= low) && !(x <= high);
}
```

Which of the following correctly identifies the bug?

What is printed as a result of the following code?

```java
int count = 0;
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    if (!(i % 2 == 0 || i % 3 == 0)) {
        count++;
    }
}
System.out.println(count);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int x = 6;
int y = 3;
boolean a = x % 2 == 0;
boolean b = y > 4;

if (!(a && b))
{
    x += 2;
}

if (!a || b)
{
    y += 5;
}
else
{
    y--;
}

System.out.println(x + " " + y);
```
